\begin_layout Title
Square-root of Spacetime
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Linas Vepstas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
25 November 2016
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
What if fermions are just defects in spacetime? This is a discursive inquiry
 into the structure of spacetime, and is probably some crude reinvention
 of the simplest parts of string theory, along a different route.
 There's no depth, here, yet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper is a set of notes pertaining to a crazy idea: what if the Dirac
 sea is just the square-root of spacetime itself? That is, instead of writing
 spacetime as the 4-vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\left(\vec{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

 we instead write it as a 2-spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $x=x_{\bar{\sigma}\sigma}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 are conjugate spinor indexes, each taking values of 1,2 so that the following
 holds as a matrix relation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{\bar{\sigma}\sigma}=\left[\vec{x}\cdot\vec{\sigma}+t\mathbb{I}\right]_{\bar{\sigma}\sigma}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 are the Pauli matrices, as usual, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{I}$
\end_inset

 is the unit 2x2 matrix.
 The fancy way of saying this is that the 2-spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\bar{\sigma}\sigma}$
\end_inset

 transforms according to the adjoint representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $sl_{2}\left(\mathbb{C}\right)$
\end_inset

, which is, of course, the Lorentz group.
